The United Nation (UN) Women, European Union (EU) and Women Advocates and Research Documentation Centre (WARDC) have frowned at violence against women and demanded for an end to all forms of violence against women and girls in Nigeria and other parts of the world. The groups emphasised the need to advance campaign on Sexual Gender Base Violence (SGBV), Harmful Practices (HP) and Sexual Health and Reproduction Right (SRHR) and address the issue of violence against women and girl-child. They expressed their displeasure over this practices during a focus meeting organised by WARDC held in  Lagos on advancing strategies to address Gender Based Violence (GBV) and Harmful Practices (HP) and promote Sexual Health and Reproduction Right (SRHR). The discussants and participants at the event emphasised the need to protect women and girls in different parts of the country. The focus group meeting organised by WARDC with the support of UN Women was to implement the Spotlight Initiative Project in Lagos State. And to achieve its goal. The meeting which was held for three days took care of Lagos West, Lagos East and Lagos Central senatorial districts respectively. The meeting which was attended by Civil Societies Organisations (CSOs), Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs), Gender-Based Organisations and faith-based organisations seek to strengthen capacity and supports CSOs and women movement on Sustainable Development Goals and target SGBV, HP, SRHR in Lagos. Speaking during the focus group meeting for Lagos West Senatorial District, the Executive Director of WARDC, Dr. Abiola Akiyode-Afolabi, called for more enlightenment on the sexual and reproductive health and rights of women and girls in Nigeria. She noted that, women deserve the rights to their body integrity, noting that there is little focus on the sexual and reproductive health and rights in the country and therefore seek for more campaigns on it 